Alexithymia Helper Glasses

Intro

Alexithymia is a condition in which those who are diagnosed are unable to discern emotions in one's face. It is often called emotional blindness and it is a condition which affects many with depression, anxiety, and PTSD. Classification can be one solution to help those out with this situation. If we can get a model working in real time that updates what emotion someone is feeling it can help those with this condition have easier interactions with other people. For this I plan on using a random forest algorithm. We can also use opencv to help capture image in real time.

In[]:
import os
import cv2
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

dataset_path = r"C:\Users\adith\Downloads\emotionDataset\train"

emotion_labels = ["angry", "happy", "sad", "neutral"]

X, y = [], []

for label_idx, emotion in enumerate(emotion_labels):
    emotion_folder = os.path.join(dataset_path, emotion) 
    
    for img_name in os.listdir(emotion_folder):
        img_path = os.path.join(emotion_folder, img_name)
        
        img = cv2.imread(img_path, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)
        
        img = cv2.resize(img, (48, 48))
        
        X.append(img.flatten())
        
        y.append(label_idx)

X = np.array(X) / 255.0  
y = np.array(y)

Data

We'll need a wide array of different emotions to train our model so I've decided to use the FER 2013 dataset. The Fer 2013 dataset is great for our purposes as it has a really large range of data and all of the images are centered on the face so it cuts down on the time we have to clean the data. It also makes it so we don't have extraneous features that we have to take out from our training and will denoise our results. We have over 28,000 images in our training set and around 3000 in our test set. There are seven emotions in the dataset but for our purposes we can cut out a few to make our model more accurate.

Pre-Processing

We will need to standardize the data first before we use it to train our model. We need to make sure to loop through the folders so we can access each image. We also need to make sure that we standardize the size and convert all of the colors to grayscale. We convert it to grayscale to cut down on processing time as we will convert this into a matrix later to process. We will only have two values instead of if we used RGB which would greatly increase the processing time as there would be many more values to go through.

Data Understanding

To fully understand exactly how we are processing our images lets try to visualize exactly how we change our images to convert them into a usable format for our purposes.

Modeling

I've decided to use the random forest classifier for our purposes. The random forest classifier is an ensemble learning method so it uses multiple decision trees which will help reduce overfitting. It also automatically selects the most important features. Faces are often quite complex so random forest works well because it handles non linearity well. Random Forest also just reduces noise as it handles multiple decision trees. Random forest works by creating multiple decision trees off of different random parts of our dataset. Each tree makes their predicitions and the forest collects them and picks the most common answer which makes it more accurate and reliable.

In[]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=47, stratify=y)


rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=47)
rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)


y_pred = rf_model.predict(X_test)



accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")


print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=emotion_labels))

Evaluation

After training my model has an accuracy of 0.51. For our metrics of measurement we are using Accuracy, Precision, recall, and F1-Score. Accuracy measures the proportion of correctly identified samples from our set. Accuracy is good as a general score but if our dataset is imbalanced it can be misleading. Recall mentions how many instances of a class were identified correctly. F1 Score ensures that there is a balance between precision and recall.

Storytelling

I've found that my model can be pretty inconsistent depending on the lighting. Its taught me that maybe random forest classifier isn't quite as complex as it needs to capture the patterns to classify emotions. Faces can all be pretty different and they aren't quite standardized so it can be hard to read into them. A neural net would probably be more better equipped to tackle this task. I've also found that a sad face is a lot harder to classify along with angry faces as they have a lot more nuance that is harder to capture with a simpler algorithm like random forest. I've found that while it is relatively good for identifying happy and neutral faces it is not great at much else so I would probably try a neural net if I wanted to put them in some smart glasses to help those with Alexithymia.

Impact

This project has many many potential impacts. If the model can be improved a little it can be used to help neurodivergent people and those with Alexithymia better identify emotions in other people and help improve the quality of their life. However, It could be used to by bad actors to identify emotions in interrogations or speechs and used as evidence to punish those for not complying with whatever they want. For example a dictator could survey the emotions of their populace while giving a speech. It would also need to be updated with many many more emotions and it might not be able to capture every nuance of emotion which might lead to bad situations for those using it.
